    notes:
      "## Pterostilbene vs Resveratrol — The Practical Decision\n**Pterostilbene advantages:**\n- ~80% oral bioavailability vs <1% for resveratrol — the dominant practical distinction\n- 6× longer plasma half-life (105 min vs 14 min)\n- Better BBB penetration\n- More selective SIRT1 activation\n- More shelf-stable\n- Lower effective doses required (100mg pterostilbene ≈ 500mg+ resveratrol in tissue exposure)\n\n**Resveratrol advantages:**\n- More extensive clinical trial database (most longevity-supplement RCTs use resveratrol, not pterostilbene)\n- Lower per-mg cost\n- Some evidence for effects pterostilbene hasn't been studied for (e.g. specific cardiovascular endpoints)\n\n**Honest framing**: for users selecting a single sirtuin activator, pterostilbene is the more pharmacokinetically favorable choice — the bioavailability advantage is dramatic and likely translates to meaningful clinical effect differences. For users running comprehensive longevity stacks, the combination of both is common (Thorne ResveraCel rationale) — small redundancy is acceptable when the cost is modest and the mechanistic case is sound. For cost-conscious users, resveratrol at higher doses (500mg+) compensates partially for the bioavailability limitation.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n100mg/day AM × 8–12 weeks. Track no specific subjective markers — sirtuin activation is largely silent. Bracket with cardiovascular markers (lipids, BP, hsCRP) at baseline and 12 weeks if cardiovascular benefit is the priority.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with: NR 300mg/day or NMN 500mg/day (substrate-product relationship — NAD+ from precursor + sirtuin activation from pterostilbene = comprehensive sirtuin pathway support; this is the Elysium Basis / Thorne ResveraCel rationale), TMG 1–2g/day (methyl-donor for NAD+ catabolism), Resveratrol 250–500mg/day (combination is common — different metabolic profiles, possible additive effects), Spermidine 1mg/day (autophagy via complementary mechanism), Urolithin A 500mg/day (mitophagy via complementary mechanism), Apigenin 50mg/day (CD38 inhibition for NAD+ preservation), Rapamycin 5–10mg weekly pulse (mTOR-pathway longevity activator).\n\n## NR + Pterostilbene — The Foundational Pairing Rationale\nElysium Health's Basis (launched 2015) was the first commercial longevity supplement to pair NR + pterostilbene specifically. The mechanistic case: NR raises cellular NAD+ levels, pterostilbene activates SIRT1 (the NAD+-dependent deacetylase that uses NAD+ as cofactor). Substrate + activator. The product was developed by Leonard Guarente's laboratory at MIT — Guarente was the original SIRT discoverer (1991 yeast SIR2 work). The NR + pterostilbene combination has more clinical trial evidence than either compound alone in this specific pairing context.\n\nFor users running a single 'longevity foundation' product, NR + pterostilbene is the most-evidence-supported simple combination. Layering additional NAD precursors (NMN, trigonelline), additional sirtuin activators (resveratrol), and downstream pathway supports (spermidine, urolithin A) builds toward comprehensive longevity stack.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule. With or without food (modest food-effect on absorption). Consistent timing helpful but not critical.\n\n## Synergies\n**NR / NMN:** substrate-product relationship; the foundational pairing. **Resveratrol:** different PK profile, possible additive effects in combination. **TMG:** methyl-donor support. **Spermidine:** autophagy via complementary mechanism. **Urolithin A:** mitophagy via complementary mechanism. **Apigenin:** CD38 inhibition for NAD+ preservation.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nRiche 2013/2014 (n=80 hypercholesterolemic adults, 125mg BID × 6–8 weeks): LDL reduction, BP improvements, no lipid panel deterioration. Dellinger 2014 (n=120 healthy adults, 50–125mg/day × 12 weeks): generally well tolerated, modest LDL effects at higher dose. Limited large-scale RCT database vs resveratrol; the Elysium Basis pivotal trial established NR + pterostilbene combination safety and NAD+ elevation but didn't isolate pterostilbene-specific effects.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized. PK profile substantially better than resveratrol — the bioavailability advantage is the central practical justification. Human RCT database smaller than resveratrol's. The Elysium / ChromaDex commercial development has produced more pterostilbene research in recent years.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic case; PK advantage well-documented; modest human RCT evidence in cardiovascular and metabolic contexts; less extensive than resveratrol's database. Anecdote: increasingly preferred in longevity-community over resveratrol due to bioavailability advantage; the Elysium Basis NR + pterostilbene combination has decade-long real-world track record. Decision frame: bioavailability-solved sirtuin activator; pairs naturally with NR (the foundational longevity pairing); useful for users who want sirtuin activation without resveratrol's bioavailability limitations.",
