    notes:
      "## Use-Case Decision Frame\nFisetin has two distinct use patterns with very different evidence bases and dosing logic:\n\n**Chronic anti-inflammatory / general health use:**\n- 100–500mg/day daily continuous\n- Treats fisetin as a flavonoid anti-inflammatory similar to quercetin\n- Long food-source exposure history establishes safety baseline\n- Modest evidence for general cardiovascular, metabolic, cognitive benefits\n- Standard fisetin form acceptable; liposomal optional\n- Mast cell stabilization for allergy/MCAS users\n\n**Senolytic burst-dose protocol:**\n- ~20mg/kg × 2 consecutive days, monthly (Mayo Clinic Yousefzadeh 2018 pattern)\n- For 70kg adult: ~1400mg × 2 days = 2800mg total per monthly cycle\n- Targets senescent cell elimination specifically\n- Bioavailability matters more — liposomal or phytosome forms preferred\n- Evidence base is emerging research; long-term safety data limited\n- The Mayo Clinic AFFIRM-LITE trial (NCT03675724) used this protocol\n- Pairs naturally with quercetin (the original Mayo D+Q dasatinib+quercetin protocol used quercetin as senolytic; fisetin emerged as a more accessible non-prescription alternative)\n\nThe two use patterns have different evidence quality and different risk-benefit calculations. Users should choose based on their specific goal and the evidence base they're comfortable with.\n\n## Mayo Clinic Senolytic Burst Protocol — Honest Framing\nThe Yousefzadeh 2018 paper identified fisetin as the most potent senolytic among nine flavonoids tested, in mouse models. The 20mg/kg × 2 days protocol pattern emerged from these studies and has been adopted in human clinical trials including AFFIRM-LITE (Mayo Clinic, NCT03675724) and AFFIRM (NCT03430037). The protocol has caught on widely in the longevity-supplement community — Andrew Huberman, Peter Attia, and other prominent voices have discussed it.\n\n**Honest evidence assessment:**\n- The mouse-model evidence is robust\n- Human clinical trial data is emerging but limited; AFFIRM-LITE and AFFIRM trials are still accumulating long-term outcomes\n- The protocol's underlying senolytic theory has substantial mechanistic support but the practical clinical benefits in humans are not yet fully characterized\n- Long-term safety data on chronic monthly burst dosing in humans is limited\n- The bioavailability issue means standard fisetin at the protocol dose may not achieve the plasma concentrations the mouse studies demonstrate; liposomal/phytosome forms are likely more effective for the senolytic mechanism specifically\n\nUsers adopting the Mayo Clinic burst-dose protocol should do so with awareness that:\n1. The protocol is evidence-supported but not yet definitively proven in humans\n2. Liposomal/phytosome forms may matter substantially for achieving senolytic-relevant concentrations\n3. The cycling pattern (2 days on, ~28 days off) is mechanistically rational and limits exposure\n4. Combined with quercetin (the original Mayo D+Q senolytic pair) may enhance the effect\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nFor chronic anti-inflammatory use: standard fisetin 100mg/day × 4 weeks, then 200–500mg/day if continuing. For senolytic burst protocol: liposomal fisetin 1500mg/day × 2 days, monthly. Bracket with comprehensive longevity panel (lipids, glucose, hsCRP, kidney function) at baseline and 12 weeks.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nFull senolytic stack: liposomal fisetin 1500mg + quercetin (Quercefit) 500mg × 2 days, monthly (the modern non-prescription D+Q analog); chronic anti-inflammatory layer with apigenin 50mg/day, spermidine 1mg/day, urolithin A 500mg/day; foundational longevity stack (NR + pterostilbene + TMG + resveratrol + omega-3 + vitamin D3 + magnesium); rapamycin 5–10mg weekly pulse (the prescription mTOR-pathway longevity activator); metformin (if indicated for metabolic context).\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder, or liposomal liquid. Liposomal fisetin: liquid suspension, hold under tongue 30 seconds before swallowing for partial sublingual absorption (some products), or swallow directly per label.\n\n## Synergies\n**Quercetin:** the natural senolytic pairing — Mayo Clinic D+Q protocol used dasatinib (chemotherapy) + quercetin; fisetin + quercetin is the non-prescription analog. **Apigenin:** complementary CD38 inhibition / NAD+ preservation. **Spermidine:** complementary autophagy mechanism (autophagy and senolysis are related but distinct cellular cleanup pathways). **Urolithin A:** mitophagy via complementary mechanism. **NMN / NR + pterostilbene:** broader longevity-stack pairing.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nYousefzadeh 2018 (EBioMedicine, mouse models): identified fisetin as most potent among nine flavonoids tested for senolytic activity; established the 20mg/kg × 2 days protocol. **The foundational paper.** AFFIRM-LITE (NCT03675724, Mayo Clinic): fisetin in older adults; outcomes data emerging. AFFIRM (NCT03430037, Mayo Clinic): fisetin in elderly women with frailty; ongoing. AlphaFisetin trial (NCT05587270): fisetin in chronic kidney disease. Multiple animal models of aging-related disease show benefits.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized in cell and animal models. Mayo Clinic-affiliated research backing. Human clinical trial data emerging but not yet definitive. Long-term safety profile from food-source exposure is exceptional; supplemental burst-dose long-term safety is less established.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid foundational mouse-model evidence; emerging human clinical trial data; mechanism well-characterized; the bioavailability limitation likely affects practical clinical effects of the senolytic protocol with standard fisetin forms. Anecdote: substantial longevity-community adoption of the Mayo burst-dose protocol; subjective effects during burst doses include modest GI upset, occasional 'senolysis flu' (transient malaise during 2-day window); long-term subjective effects modest. Decision frame: chronic low-dose use as flavonoid anti-inflammatory has solid food-source evidence; burst-dose senolytic protocol is mechanistically rational and has Mayo Clinic research backing but the human clinical evidence is still emerging; liposomal/phytosome forms likely matter substantially for senolytic protocols.",
