    sourcingNotes:
      "OTC supplement. Form selection matters substantially. Reputable brands: **Quercefit (Indena phytosome)** — the most-evidence-supported bioavailability-enhanced form; ~20× absorption improvement over standard quercetin; brands using Quercefit include Thorne Quercetin Phytosome, Pure Encapsulations Quercefit. **Liposomal quercetin** — Pure Encapsulations Liposomal Quercetin, Quicksilver Scientific Liposomal Quercetin. **Standard quercetin dihydrate** — Doctor's Best Quercetin, NOW Foods Quercetin with Bromelain, Solgar Quercetin Complex with Ester-C. Cost: standard form $20–40/month; phytosome and liposomal forms $40–100/month.",
    notes:
      "## Form Selection — Practical Decision\n**Standard quercetin dihydrate:** the original form; cost-effective; poor bioavailability (~1–2%); the form used in most clinical trials (so the trial evidence applies to this form even with the bioavailability limitation). For chronic mast cell stabilization at 500–1000mg/day, standard form provides adequate clinical effect.\n\n**Quercefit / Quercetin phytosome (Indena):** phospholipid complex; ~20× absorption improvement; the most-evidence-supported bioavailability-enhanced form. Modern clinical research increasingly uses Quercefit. Lower effective doses (250–500mg) achieve similar tissue exposure to standard form at higher doses.\n\n**Liposomal quercetin:** liposomal delivery; substantial bioavailability improvement; less RCT evidence specifically vs Quercefit but mechanistically similar advantage.\n\n**Quercetin + bromelain (traditional combination):** bromelain (pineapple-derived proteolytic enzyme) is the traditional pairing — bromelain enhances quercetin absorption and adds its own anti-inflammatory effects via different mechanism. The combination is commercially available in many seasonal allergy products.\n\n**Decision frame:**\n- **Allergy/MCAS support:** standard quercetin + bromelain combination (the traditional pairing); Quercefit for users wanting better absorption with lower pill burden\n- **Senolytic protocols:** Quercefit or liposomal — bioavailability matters more for senescent-cell elimination\n- **Antiviral context:** standard form at higher doses; Quercefit for lower doses with similar tissue exposure\n- **Cost-conscious users:** standard quercetin + bromelain; works adequately for most use cases\n\n## Mast Cell Stabilization Use Case\nQuercetin's strongest evidence base is for mast cell stabilization — reducing histamine release in allergic and MCAS contexts. This use case has been documented since the 1980s and is reflected in many commercial seasonal allergy products combining quercetin with bromelain, vitamin C, and stinging nettle.\n\nFor seasonal allergy: 500–1000mg/day starting 2–4 weeks before allergy season, continuing through season. For MCAS: continuous 1000–2000mg/day, typically with bromelain. The histamine-reduction effect is generally subjectively perceptible — users with significant histamine load often notice meaningful symptom reduction within 1–2 weeks.\n\n## Senolytic Use Case — D+Q and Beyond\nThe Mayo Clinic dasatinib + quercetin (D+Q) protocol was the original senolytic identification (Zhu 2015, foundational paper). Dasatinib (a tyrosine kinase inhibitor chemotherapy) + quercetin together produced senolytic effect; the synergy was important — neither monotherapy was as effective as the combination. Subsequent human trials including Justice 2019 (idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis) used the D+Q protocol.\n\nFor non-clinical longevity contexts, dasatinib is rarely accessible (prescription chemotherapy with significant side effects). Quercetin alone has weaker senolytic activity than the D+Q combination, but fisetin emerged as a more potent non-prescription flavonoid senolytic (Yousefzadeh 2018). Modern non-prescription senolytic protocols typically pair fisetin + quercetin in burst-dose patterns analogous to the original D+Q approach but without the chemotherapy component.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nFor allergy/MCAS: standard quercetin 500mg BID with bromelain × 4 weeks. For chronic anti-inflammatory: 500–1000mg/day. For senolytic burst protocol: 500mg Quercefit + 1500mg liposomal fisetin × 2 days, monthly. Bracket with hsCRP and inflammatory markers if relevant to use case.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nComprehensive flavonoid stack: Quercetin (Quercefit) 500mg/day + Apigenin 50mg/day + Fisetin 200mg/day chronic + monthly fisetin/quercetin burst-dose senolytic protocol. Foundational longevity stack: NR + pterostilbene + TMG + resveratrol + spermidine + urolithin A + omega-3 + vitamin D3 + magnesium. Rapamycin pulse-dosing weekly. Lifestyle: time-restricted eating, structured exercise, sleep optimization.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder, or liposomal liquid. With food preferred (modest food-effect on absorption). Bromelain pairing requires both compounds in same time frame.\n\n## Synergies\n**Bromelain:** the classical pairing — enzymatic absorption enhancement + complementary anti-inflammatory mechanism. **Fisetin:** the modern non-prescription senolytic pairing (analog of the original D+Q protocol). **Apigenin:** complementary flavonoid mechanism + CD38 inhibition. **Vitamin C:** synergistic antioxidant and immune support. **Stinging nettle:** traditional allergy-support pairing.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nZhu 2015 (Aging Cell): foundational D+Q senolytic identification paper. Justice 2019 (idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis pilot, n=14): D+Q protocol showed improvements in physical function. Hickson 2019 (n=9 diabetic kidney disease): D+Q protocol showed senescent cell marker reduction. Larson 2012 (meta-analysis of quercetin BP studies): modest systolic BP reduction. Riva 2019 (Quercefit n=22 healthy adults): improved exercise performance markers. Edwards 2007 (n=41 hypertensive adults, 730mg/day × 28 days): systolic BP reduction.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nSubstantial flavonoid research base. Mast cell stabilization mechanism well-characterized. Senolytic activity established as part of D+Q protocol. Bioavailability limitations of standard form well-documented; bioavailability-enhanced forms have improving evidence base.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid evidence for mast cell stabilization and allergy/MCAS support; modest evidence for senolytic activity (foundational role in D+Q research); cardiovascular and exercise performance evidence accumulating. Anecdote: extensive use in allergy/MCAS contexts with positive subjective reports; senolytic-burst use in longevity community. Decision frame: foundational allergy/anti-inflammatory supplement; useful adjunct in senolytic protocols (paired with fisetin); bioavailability-enhanced forms (Quercefit) preferred for users wanting clinical-grade effect at lower doses.",
