    mechanism:
      "Isothiocyanate (ITC) compound produced when the precursor glucosinolate **glucoraphanin** is hydrolyzed by the enzyme **myrosinase**. The two compounds (glucoraphanin and myrosinase) exist in separate plant cell compartments and only react when plant tissue is damaged (chewing, chopping, crushing). The hydrolysis reaction converts inactive glucoraphanin into bioactive sulforaphane. **Source biology — broccoli sprouts**: the Talalay laboratory at Johns Hopkins published the foundational 1997 paper identifying broccoli sprouts as containing 10–100× more glucoraphanin than mature broccoli. The 3-day-old broccoli sprout is the practical optimum for sulforaphane production — high glucoraphanin content with active myrosinase. Mature broccoli has substantial glucoraphanin but the cooking required for palatability often inactivates myrosinase. **Practical sulforaphane production approaches**: (1) **Fresh broccoli sprouts** (the Rhonda Patrick-popularized approach) — grow at home (3-day sprouting protocol) or buy fresh; eat raw or lightly steamed (>70°C inactivates myrosinase); ~100g sprouts delivers substantial sulforaphane. (2) **Mature broccoli with myrosinase preserved** — light steaming for <4 minutes preserves enzyme; raw broccoli; pairing cooked broccoli with mustard seeds (which contain myrosinase) restores enzymatic conversion. (3) **Standardized sulforaphane supplements** — pre-formed sulforaphane (more direct delivery, more expensive) or glucoraphanin + myrosinase (the Truebroc and similar formulations). **Mechanism — Nrf2 master regulator activation**: sulforaphane is the most-studied Nrf2 (Nuclear factor erythroid 2-related factor 2) activator in nutrition science. Nrf2 is the master regulator of the cellular antioxidant response — when activated, it translocates to the nucleus and induces transcription of >200 cytoprotective genes including: glutathione synthesis enzymes (glutamate-cysteine ligase, glutathione synthetase), antioxidant enzymes (superoxide dismutase, catalase, glutathione peroxidase), phase II detoxification enzymes (NQO1, GST, UGT, sulfotransferases), heme oxygenase-1 (HO-1, anti-inflammatory + cytoprotective), thioredoxin reductase, and many others. This master regulator activation means sulforaphane upregulates the cell's entire endogenous antioxidant and detoxification response simultaneously — a fundamentally different mechanism from direct antioxidants (vitamin C, vitamin E, glutathione supplementation) which provide one specific antioxidant rather than upregulating the whole cellular system. **Mechanism — beyond Nrf2**: NF-κB inhibition (anti-inflammatory); HDAC (histone deacetylase) inhibition affecting epigenetic regulation; possible direct antimicrobial effects against H. pylori and various pathogens; effects on autophagy via Nrf2 pathway interactions with mTOR; emerging evidence for effects on cancer cell apoptosis via multiple pathways. **Effects in human RCTs**: improvements in oxidative stress markers, reductions in inflammatory cytokines, beneficial effects on cardiovascular markers, modest blood pressure reduction, glycemic control improvements in T2D, possible cognitive benefits emerging, autism spectrum disorder symptom modulation (Singh 2014 trial — significant clinical improvements that drew substantial attention), H. pylori antibacterial effects.",
